23. quoe solitus se. cantare, “what (Amphion) was accustomed to sin .'’ 2g4. Amphion Dircaezts. Amphion was a king of Thebes, and the hus- band of Niobe: marvellous stories are told of the wonderful effects produced by the sound of his lyre3 not only did the oxen follow him, but the very stones obeyed the strain. He is said to have killed him- self for grief, because his children had been slain by Apollo and Diana. The sorrow of his wife Niobe formed a very tragic subject, which poets and sculptors worked out with great effect. Dirce was a relative of the family, who had ill-used Amphion's mother, Antiope; Amphion tied her to a bun, and allowing her to be dragged about till she died, he threw the body into a well, which took the name of “ Dirce.’' This well was near Thebes in Boeotia3 and so the term ‘¹ Dircaean ” is often used poetically for Boeotian. See Smith's Diet. Biog, art. Amphion3 and cf. Ovid. Met. VI. 266—312.

in Actoeo Aracyntho. The mountain Aracynthus which is best known was in Acarnania or AEtolia; but there is no evidence that Amphion was ever in that part of the country.
